In Java you can create an array of class references using the syntax

    Class&lt;?&gt;[] arrayOfClasses = {A.class, B.class, C.class};

and access them as below using newInstance()

    Object a = arrayOfClasses[0].newInstance();

You can find the documentation here: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/reflect/member/ctorInstance.html

I recommend using a no-args default constructor to create a new instance of a given `Class` as the `Class#newInstance` method becomes deprecated as of Java 9. Remember it uses reflection under the hood which is quite slow and should be avoided if possible. Perhaps you want to disclose what you try to achieve.

```java
private static Object newInstance(final Class&lt;?&gt; type) {
	try {
		Object object = type.getDeclaredConstructor().newInstance();
		System.out.println(&quot;Created a new instance of &quot; + object.getClass());
		return object;
	} catch (InstantiationException | NoSuchMethodException | InvocationTargetException | IllegalAccessException e) {
		throw new RuntimeException(e);
	}
}
```
```java
static class A {}
static class B {}
static class C {}
```
____

The array declaration and usage are simple, but I recommend using a `List&lt;Class&lt;?&gt;&gt;`:
```java
List&lt;Class&lt;?&gt;&gt; classes = List.of(A.class, B.class, C.class);
List&lt;Object&gt; list = classes.stream().map(Application::newInstance).toList();
```
&gt; ```
&gt; Created a new instance of class com.company.Application$A
&gt; Created a new instance of class com.company.Application$B
&gt; Created a new instance of class com.company.Application$C
&gt; ```
... or a single call:
```java
Object object = newInstance(classes.get(0));
```
&gt; ```
&gt; Created a new instance of class com.company.Application$A
&gt; ```

I think the example with reflection looks reasonable:

```java
List&lt;Class&lt;?&gt;&gt; classes = List.of(A.class, B.class, C.class);

for(Class&lt;?&gt; clazz : classes)
    Object obj = clazz.newInstance();
```

But I think this can be improved with using `Supplier` an not using Reflection:

```java
List&lt;Supplier&lt;Object&gt;&gt; suppliers = List.of(A::new, B::new, C::new);

for(Supplier&lt;Object&gt; supplier : suppliers)
    Object obj = supplier.get();
```

I find it more flexible and more OOP support.

A more *functional* approach, without using Reflection.

````
class A {}
class B {}
class C {}

Supplier&lt;?&gt;[] arrayOfSupplier = { A::new, B::new, C::new };
// or
Supplier&lt;?&gt;[] arrayOfSupplier = { () -&gt; new A(), () -&gt; new B(), () -&gt; new C() };
    
Object a = arrayOfSupplier[0].get();
````

`A::new` is a method reference to the no-argument constructor;  
similar to the lambda expression `() -&gt; new A()`.

