answers.body_markdown:
You don&#39;t need to ever call that method. Consider it internal API used by `ZipInputStream` and co itself.

This is how you write a file to a `ZipOutputStream`:

```
try (var out = new ZipOutputStream(someStream)) {
  out.putNextEntry(new ZipEntry(&quot;myfile.txt&quot;));
  out.write(&quot;Hello, World!&quot;.getBytes());
  out.putNextEntry(new ZipEntry(&quot;file2.txt&quot;));
  out.write(&quot;Goodbye!&quot;.getBytes());
}
```

This produces a perfectly valid zip file - there is no need to call `.setSize()`, or any `.set` method, on those `ZipEntry` objects. This is perhaps not the best API design (it leads to confusion, and there is effectively zero benefit to being able to pass a `ZipEntry` object to the `putNextEntry` method - that really should have just taken a string or `Path` object instead). But, that&#39;s how the API works.

Of course, when you obtain `ZipEntry` objects (because you are using `ZipInputStream` or reading from a `ZipFile` object), CRC, size, and all those other properties just are what they are - set to what the entry in the zip file has. You can call the setters on them if you want to modify the object and then pass it along to some other code. Though, I can&#39;t fathom why you would possibly want to do that.

In response to why there is a _ZipEntry#setSize_ method.

The JavaDoc for [ZipOitputStream#putNextEntry](https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/blob/master/src/java.base/share/classes/java/util/zip/ZipOutputStream.java#L194) contains the following _apiNote_.

```java
/**
@apiNote When writing a directory entry, the STORED compression method
should be used and the size and CRC-32 values should be set to 0:

{@snippet lang = &quot;java&quot;:
    ZipEntry e = new ZipEntry(entryName);
    if (e.isDirectory()) {
        e.setMethod(ZipEntry.STORED);
        e.setSize(0);
        e.setCrc(0);
    }
    stream.putNextEntry(e);
}

This allows optimal performance when processing directory entries.
*/
```

